CS-499 Milestone Three Narrative
Enhancement Two: Algorithms and Data Structure
Gary Travis

Describe the artifact
The artifact I selected is my 3D scene application from CS-330 (Computational Graphics and Visualization). It is an OpenGL program written in C++ that recreates a small indoor scene I built earlier in the program. The scene has a floor, a space heater with a grill and trim, a wicker basket, a noise maker, and a small fan. The program uses GLEW and GLFW for the OpenGL context and windowing, GLM for the matrix math, and a set of shape-mesh helpers to draw the basic primitives like planes, boxes, cylinders, tapered cylinders, and torus shapes. I originally created it in November 2023 as the final project for CS-330, and I rebuilt it for the capstone in Visual Studio 2022 using vcpkg to manage the libraries.
Justify the inclusion of the artifact in my ePortfolio
I included this artifact because it gave me a clean, self-contained piece of software to demonstrate a real improvement in algorithms and data structures, which is the focus of this enhancement. In the original version, the scene was drawn by a long list of hard-coded steps. Every object had its own block of code that set a scale, a rotation, a position, picked a texture, and then called the matching draw function by hand. Adding or moving an object meant editing the render code directly, and there was no clean way to attach one object to another so they moved together.
For the enhancement I reworked the scene from those hard-coded draw calls into a small data-driven scene graph. The specific components that show off my skills are:
A SceneObject struct that stores everything one object needs in one place. It holds the mesh type, the position, rotation, and scale (stored relative to its parent), the color or texture, and an index pointing at its parent object.
A std::vector<SceneObject> that holds the entire scene as data, so the scene is described in one BuildSceneGraph() function instead of being scattered through the render loop.
An enum class MeshType instead of passing mesh names around as strings, so the compiler catches a bad mesh choice and a typo can never select the wrong shape.
A std::unordered_map<MeshType, std::function<void()>> mesh registry that maps each mesh type to the little function that draws it. This replaces a long if/else chain with an O(1) lookup, so the render loop just looks the mesh up instead of testing every option every frame.
A recursive ComputeWorldMatrix() function that walks up the parent chain to build each object's final world transform, which is how the heater grill and trim stay attached to the heater body.
A RenderScene() loop that builds an index list of objects, precomputes each world matrix once, and then uses std::sort to order the objects back-to-front by their world-space Z before drawing, so transparency and depth layer correctly.
I improved the artifact in exactly the way I planned. The biggest change is that the scene is now described by data, so the render loop never has to change when I add, remove, or re-parent an object. I just add a record to the scene graph. I also added defensive checks while building the world transforms. The parent-chain walk guards against an out-of-range parent index, an object that lists itself as its own parent, and cyclic parent references, so a bad scene definition cannot send the program into infinite recursion or read past the end of the vector. I kept the comments in my own everyday style so the code reads like notes I would actually leave for myself.
Reflect on the course outcomes
Working on this enhancement met the course outcomes I set in my Module One plan. Most directly, it demonstrates the outcome about designing and evaluating computing solutions using algorithmic principles and appropriate data structures while managing trade-offs (Outcome 3). The choice of a std::vector for the scene, an unordered_map for the mesh registry, and a recursive parent-chain walk for the transforms are all deliberate data-structure and algorithm decisions, and I weighed the trade-offs. For example, I accepted a small amount of repeated matrix work in the recursion in exchange for much simpler and safer code than caching every transform would have required.
It also supports the outcome about building professional-quality, well-founded techniques and tools in computing practices, because I moved the project to a modern build setup (Visual Studio 2022 with vcpkg), kept the code in clean C++, and added the kind of input validation and bounds checking that production code needs. Finally, it touches the outcome on communicating clearly to technical and non-technical audiences, since I documented the design in plain comments and in this narrative so a reader can follow what each data structure is doing and why.
I did not need to revise the outcomes I listed in Module One. The enhancement lined up with them as planned.
Reflect on the process
The biggest thing I learned was how much easier a system is to reason about once the data is separated from the behavior. In the original code the "what to draw" and the "how to draw it" were tangled together, so any change risked breaking something unrelated. Pulling the scene out into a SceneObject struct and a vector made the program feel like it had an actual design instead of just a script of draw calls.
I ran into a few real challenges along the way. The first was getting the project to build cleanly with vcpkg. I had to enable GLM_ENABLE_EXPERIMENTAL because the newer GLM version requires it for the transform header, and I had to set the project's include directories and working directory correctly. The second challenge, and the one that cost me the most time, was a window that opened completely black even though the build and OpenGL initialization both succeeded. After reading the console output I found the real cause. The program could not open the shader files because the working directory was wrong when it was launched outside of the debugger. I fixed it by adding a small helper that locates the asset folder at runtime and switches into it, so the shaders and textures load no matter how the program is started. That turned out to be a good lesson in not assuming the working directory, since a relative path is only as reliable as the folder you launch from. Debugging that issue by reading the actual error message instead of guessing was the part of the process I am most glad I worked through.

